@Tutorial(time: 15) {
    @Intro(title: "VoiceOver: Tap Targets") {
        After Steps 1 and 2 every control announces with a clear label and short Voice Control input names. But the contact list itself is still broken in a way that doesn't show up in inspection â€” it navigates via `.onTapGesture`, which means VoiceOver gets no signal that the row is interactive. The user sees a sea of individually-focusable text and image elements with no "Button" trait, no "double-tap to activate" hint, and no way to trigger the navigation a sighted user takes for granted.

        @Video(source: 03-intro.mp4, alt: "Screen recording: VoiceOver moving through a contact row, stopping on every individual child element â€” avatar, name, role, company, conference, each tag, the star â€” with no surrounding 'Button' trait to show the row navigates anywhere.")
    }

    @Section(title: "Why `.onTapGesture` is invisible to VoiceOver") {
        @ContentAndMedia {
            `.onTapGesture` registers a closure for sighted touch input. VoiceOver doesn't surface it as an action because â€” from the assistive technology's perspective â€” there's no element that announces itself as actionable. The row's children come through individually, but none of them are tappable, and the row's parent isn't a button. A VoiceOver user can swipe past every element of a row without ever discovering they're inside a navigation control.

            `NavigationLink` is the semantic component for "this view navigates somewhere." When SwiftUI sees one in a `NavigationStack`, it automatically:

            - Adds the `.isButton` accessibility trait so VoiceOver announces "Button" along with the row's label.
            - Adds the standard activation hint â€” VoiceOver speaks "Double-tap to activate."
            - Combines the children into a single focus stop, so the user swipes once per row instead of once per element.
            - Hands activation off to the `navigationDestination(for:)` modifier on the enclosing stack.

            None of that is opt-in. You get it by using the right SwiftUI component. The fix in this step is mechanical â€” *unwrap* the tap gesture and put `NavigationLink` back where it belongs.

        }
    }

    @Section(title: "Wrap the row in `NavigationLink`") {
        @ContentAndMedia {
            The row currently sits directly inside the `ForEach`, with `.contentShape(.rect)` and `.onTapGesture` doing the navigation. Wrap `ContactRowView(...)` in a value-based `NavigationLink` instead â€” the row becomes the link's *label content*, and the navigation value is the `Contact` itself. Apply `.buttonStyle(.plain)` so the link doesn't pick up the system's blue tint and capsule highlight.

        }

        @Steps {
            @Step {
                Find the `ForEach(filteredContacts)` in `ContactListView.swift`. The row is followed by `.contentShape(.rect)` and `.onTapGesture { selectedContact = contact }`.

                @Code(name: "ContactListView.swift", file: 03-row-before.swift)
            }

            @Step {
                Wrap `ContactRowView(...)` in `NavigationLink(value: contact) { ... }` and chain `.buttonStyle(.plain)` on the link itself. Delete `.contentShape(.rect)` and `.onTapGesture` â€” `NavigationLink` is what registers the activation now.

                @Code(name: "ContactListView.swift", file: 03-row-after.swift, previousFile: 03-row-before.swift)
            }
        }
    }

    @Section(title: "Restore the typed navigation destination") {
        @ContentAndMedia {
            With `NavigationLink` emitting `Contact` values into the stack, the destination modifier needs to switch from item-binding to type-based handling. The `@State private var selectedContact: Contact?` is no longer needed â€” `NavigationStack` owns the navigation state once the link drives it.

        }

        @Steps {
            @Step {
                Locate the `@State private var selectedContact: Contact?` near the other `@State` declarations, and the `.navigationDestination(item: $selectedContact)` modifier on the body's `ZStack`.

                @Code(name: "ContactListView.swift", file: 03-cleanup-before.swift)
            }

            @Step {
                Delete the `selectedContact` `@State` line. Change `.navigationDestination(item: $selectedContact)` to `.navigationDestination(for: Contact.self)` â€” `NavigationStack` will route the value the link emits.

                @Code(name: "ContactListView.swift", file: 03-cleanup-after.swift, previousFile: 03-cleanup-before.swift)
            }
        }
    }

    @Section(title: "Verify with VoiceOver") {
        @ContentAndMedia {
            Run with VoiceOver and swipe through the list. Each row is now a single focus stop announced as a Button â€” the trait that drives "Double-tap to activate." Double-tapping navigates to the detail screen, just like the sighted tap does.

            The combined label is still the default child concatenation, with the most important information ("Needs follow-up", "Favorited") buried at the end. That's what Step 4 (Grouping) addresses by composing an explicit `.accessibilityLabel`. For now, the *interaction* is fixed even if the *announcement* still needs work.

            The finished snapshot lives in `Steps/03-VoiceOver-TapTargets/Finished/`.

            @Video(source: 03-verify.mp4, poster: 03-verify-poster.png, alt: "The simulator's contact list beside the Accessibility Inspector, a contact row selected as a single element whose combined label ends in 'Button'. Play to see a double-tap navigate to the detail screen.")
        }
    }
}
